 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume IV deBethune was born about 1236, in France, his father, Guillaume de Béthune IV, was 12 and his mother, Beatrix Catherine de Hebuterne, was 14. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Jeanne de Nesle Falvy. He died in 1279, at the age of 44."},"et":{"ABT 1236–1279":"umbes 1236–1279","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1236–1279":"1236–1279","–1280":"–1280","1270–1340":"1270–1340","1272–1339":"1272–1339","1280–1324":"1280–1324","–1340":"–1340","1225–1248":"1225–1248","1223–1255":"1223–1255","ABT 1236":"umbes 1236","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","abt. 1272":"umbes 1272","1280":"1280","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1324":"1324","1236":"1236","1279":"1279","1223":"1223","1255":"1255","1339":"1339","Lorkeren, East Flanders, Belgium":"Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia","of Flavy, Oise or Aisne, France":"Flavy-le-Martel, Aisne, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Locres, France":"Prantsusmaa","Loker, West-Vlaanderen, België":"Loker, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fi":{"ABT 1236–1279":"noin 1236–1279","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1236–1279":"1236–1279","–1280":"–1280","1270–1340":"1270–1340","1272–1339":"1272–1339","1280–1324":"1280–1324","–1340":"–1340","1225–1248":"1225–1248","1223–1255":"1223–1255","ABT 1236":"noin 1236","1340":"1340","1272":"1272","1270":"1270","abt. 1272":"noin 1272","1280":"1280","1205":"1205","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1324":"1324","1236":"1236","1279":"1279","1223":"1223","1255":"1255","1339":"1339","Lorkeren, East Flanders, Belgium":"Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia","of Flavy, Oise or Aisne, France":"Flavy-le-Martel, Aisne, Picardie, Ranska","Locres, France":"Ranska","Loker, West-Vlaanderen, België":"Loker, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fr":{"ABT 1236–1279":"environ 1236–1279","1205–Female":"1205–Décédée","1236–1279":"1236–1279","–1280":"–1280","1270–1340":"1270–1340",